               <p>MR. BODKIN conducted the prosecution.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-225-person1676">
                  JAMES 
                  HILL
               <interp inst="t18310908-225-person1676" type="surname" value="HILL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-225-person1676" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-225-person1676" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am vestry-clerk to St. James, Clerkenwell. I produce an examined copy of the register of the marriage, in the church of St. Philip and St. James, Bristol, and likewise an extract of the register of St. James, Clerkenwell - I have compared them both with the books, and they are correct.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-225-person1677">
                  STEPHEN 
                  JONES
               <interp inst="t18310908-225-person1677" type="surname" value="JONES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-225-person1677" type="given" value="STEPHEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-225-person1677" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a shoemaker, and live in Gloucestershire. I know the prisoner; I was at his wedding at the church of St. Philip and St. James, Bristol; I think it will be sixteen years ago in October - he married 
               
                  <persName id="t18310908-225-victim1679" type="victimName">
                     Martha 
                     Short
                  <interp inst="t18310908-225-victim1679" type="surname" value="Short"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-225-victim1679" type="given" value="Martha"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-225-victim1679" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
            ; I knew them living together as husband and wife for two or three years - I believe they had three or four children; I was overseer of the parish at the time - I saw his wife at my house on the 27th of August last.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-225-victim1680" type="victimName">
                  MARIA 
                  WARBOYS
               <interp inst="t18310908-225-victim1680" type="surname" value="WARBOYS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-225-victim1680" type="given" value="MARIA"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-225-victim1680" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I married the prisoner at Clerkenwell church on the <rs id="t18310908-225-cd1157" type="crimeDate">4th of October, 1825</rs>
                  <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310908-225-off1156 t18310908-225-cd1157"></join> - he lived with me two years, and it will be four years on the 25th of October next since he was taken by the Bristol officers on account of his first marriage; I did not know at the time of our marriage that he had a wife - the officers told me of it; I then asked him to tell me, and he said it was so.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-225-person1681">
                  JAMES 
                  WARBOYS
               <interp inst="t18310908-225-person1681" type="surname" value="WARBOYS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-225-person1681" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-225-person1681" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the brother of Maria Warboys; I gave her away on her marriage to the prisoner - he always denied having a wife; my mother told him she had been very nearly bit two or three times, and she hoped she would not again - this was the night before the marriage; he positively denied having been married before.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I was drinking at a public-house all night -I was taken from there to church; I had not a single farthing - she paid for all. Witness. It is quite false - my sister had not a farthing in her pocket, and I am sure I did not pay.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-225-person1682">
                  SAMUEL 
                  MOUNTSTEVENS
               <interp inst="t18310908-225-person1682" type="surname" value="MOUNTSTEVENS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-225-person1682" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-225-person1682" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a beadle of Clerkenwell. I removed the prisoner and his family to Gloucestershire in May last; in going down his wife was troubling him, as she was fearful they would go to Bristol, and find his other wife - he told her to be quiet, she had nothing to fear.(The certificates were put in and read.)</p>
